    <node id=" Suzy. You've got a whole section on assessment, I don't know—&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: This isn't about assessment.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Oh, okay. Go on, then.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: So, on the basis that this is not about assessment, you mentioned that one of the lessons learned from Scotland is that they said they spent too much time on curriculum content rather than assessment. Can you tell me a little bit about what you've learned about how they quality control the content, even though the content, of course, will be completely different in Wales?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, the content would be completely different. When I said they spent too much time, I said that the focus had been in their work about just talking about content and, actually, the assessment arrangements were bolted on at the end of the process. So, the curriculum was all designed and developed, it was sent out to schools, and then the question was raised: 'Oh, actually, what assessment methods—? How are going to assess how children are getting on?' But, Steve, you would have more details of their" />
    <node id="The speakers in the transcript are discussing the implementation of a new curriculum in Wales, which includes the development of &quot;what matters&quot; statements that outline key concepts to be taught in each area of learning (AoLE). The initial plan is to include these statements in secondary legislation, meaning they can be easily amended as needed. However, Suzy Davies AM suggests that placing the wording of the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in primary legislation would provide greater certainty at the outset and allow for easier changes in the future via affirmative procedure secondary legislation.&#10;&#10;Kirsty Williams AM agrees with the concern about certainty but explains that they want to ensure flexibility, as societal understanding of various topics may change over time. She emphasizes that the &quot;what matters&quot; statements are developed by practitioners and experts, not Ministers or civil servants. Lynne Neagle AM clarifies that the Bill will include a statutory provision for the &quot;what matters&quot; statements, bringing it down one step further from just having them at the AoLE level.&#10;&#10;Hefin David AM raises concerns about consistency in implementing the new curriculum and accountability, to which Kirsty Williams AM responds by stating they are working on ensuring greater consistency through a statutory framework for progression steps within each AoLE area.&#10;&#10;In summary, Suzy Davies AM suggests placing the wording of the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in primary legislation for certainty and ease of change, while Kirsty Williams AM and Lynne Neagle AM explain their preference for including them in secondary legislation to ensure flexibility, as societal understanding of various topics may change over time. The discussion also touches on addressing concerns about consistency and accountability in implementing the new curriculum." />
