    <node id="The main messages received during the feedback period on the draft curriculum for the new Welsh curriculum indicate that the principles were broadly supported, with positive feedback regarding the emphasis placed on ongoing assessment to support children's learning and progression. However, there were suggestions to find a better way of expressing the purposes of assessment. The level of feedback was significant, as stated by Kirsty Williams AM, who mentioned a concerted effort and a plan drawn up to ensure that there was extensive engagement in providing feedback on the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;The Learned Society of Wales recommended creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum. This proposal is being considered as part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum, according to Kirsty Williams AM. No specific details about the extent or nature of the feedback have been provided in the transcript, but it is clear that various groups and individuals contributed to the feedback process." />
    <node id="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee this morning. I've received no apologies for absence. Suzy Davies is going to be arriving a little bit late. Are there any declarations of interest, please? No? Okay. Item 2, then, this morning is an evidence session to scrutinise the Welsh Government's progress in developing the new curriculum for Wales. I'm very pleased to welcome Kirsty Williams AM, Minister for Education; Steve Davies, director of the education directorate; and Claire Bennett, who is deputy director for curriculum and assessment. Thank you all for attending this morning, and thank you for the paper that you provided in advance to the committee. We've got a lot of ground to cover, so if it's okay, we'll go straight into questions. If I can just start by asking you what the main messages are that you've received during the feedback period on the draft curriculum.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Chair. If I may, I think it's important to understand what the level of that feedback has been. So, there was a concerted effort and a plan drawn up to try and ensure that there was as" />
