    <node id=": Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And I think that's another difference, you see—that strong middle tier and the role that the middle tier is playing in Wales, which was absent in Scotland. So, this ability to work in networks to provide support to a network of schools, that wasn't available in the Scottish system and I think that makes—I think that helps us in the way that they just simply didn't have a structure that allowed them to do that. It's not a criticism of them; it's just that we have got a structure that we can utilise to do that support so that schools are not completely left on their own and they can be working with other schools, with their regional consortia, going forward.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Can I just have a quick—?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Very quickly, because I want to move on to implementation.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Yes, sorry, I completely understand. Was one of the things that Scotland did—I don't want to use the word 'assess'—to monitor the pupil response to the curriculum as one of the means of deciding whether curricula in particular schools" />
    <node id="'t want to use the word 'assess'—to monitor the pupil response to the curriculum as one of the means of deciding whether curricula in particular schools were working well enough?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I don't know if they—. I don't know if they did, but one of the interesting things that we were reflecting on over the weekend is that, certainly some of the Canadian systems, in particular, which we were interested in, used pupil surveys as part of their accountability regime—so, actually taking the time to ask students how they felt, not just about the content of the new curriculum, but actually how they felt their school was doing. And so we're interested in looking, as I said, at some of the practices that other countries use to include pupil voice to find out what's happening.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay, that's interesting. Okay, thank you.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes. I mean, it's early thoughts, because we've only just heard about it ourselves. But that's the beauty of working with other countries. They found that particular useful and successful, and we're keen to see if we could do something similar" />
    <node id="1. The new curriculum is being implemented using a strategy where smaller groups of pioneer schools work together to create and test materials through cluster groups. This iterative process involves feedback from external experts, further development in pioneer schools, and refining by regions.&#10;2. Sixty applicants were chosen from 170 previous pioneer schools as innovation schools, with four per region. These schools are examining the curriculum as a whole and its practical application in their specific context.&#10;3. Reports from these innovation schools have been compiled into an overall report by research company Wavehill, highlighting themes emerging from headteachers' perspectives on implementing the curriculum in their schools.&#10;4. With a clear understanding of the curriculum's structure, cluster groups play an essential role in helping individual schools implement it in a practical manner. Regional consortia provide differentiated professional learning support for schools at various stages of implementation, emphasizing peer-to-peer sharing and collaboration.&#10;5. Headteachers have been engaged in detailed discussions about the application of the new curriculum, providing valuable insights into its practical implementation in their schools.&#10;&#10;To implement the new curriculum in a practical manner, schools can follow these steps:&#10;a) Review the new curriculum and guidance documents, considering how it applies to their specific context.&#10;b) Engage with cluster groups for support, as they play an essential role in implementing the curriculum at this stage. Collaborate with other schools, teachers, and headteachers to share experiences, resources, and best practices.&#10;c) Utilize regional consortia to access differentiated professional learning support tailored to the school's unique implementation stage.&#10;d) Leverage insights from detailed discussions held by headteachers on the curriculum's application to ensure a practical and well-thought-out approach in their schools." />
    <node id="1. Kirsty Williams AM's Viewpoint:&#10;Kirsty Williams AM, as the Minister for Education in Wales, supports the teaching of Relationships and Sex Education (RSE) in schools. She believes that RSE is an important aspect of the curriculum, which can help achieve the four purposes of the Welsh education system, such as creating healthy, confident individuals and ethical, informed citizens.&#10;&#10;2. Key Messages Emphasized by Those Who Opposed the Inclusion of RSE:&#10;Individuals opposing the inclusion of RSE in schools raised key messages that emphasized their viewpoints. They questioned whether children should be taught RSE at all and argued against its inclusion in the curriculum, believing it should not be a compulsory part of the curriculum. These individuals believed that issues around relationships and sexuality education were not an area where the school system and the education system should be involved, but rather the preserve of parents to teach children about such matters. Some also raised concerns regarding potential challenges for staff in talking about issues they may personally disagree with in relation to this curriculum. Additionally, there was a strong view that parents, and parents alone, should make decisions about whether their children should have access to the entirety of the curriculum rather than schools or the state setting those rules." />
    <node id=" parents to teach children about issues around relationships and sexuality education. There were some issues raised about potential challenges with staff in talking about issues that they perhaps personally did not agree with with regard to this curriculum. So, those were the main areas that people were concerned about. With regard to guaranteed access to a full curriculum, there were strong views that, again, it should be parents, and parents alone, that made decisions about whether their children should have access to the entirety of the curriculum rather than schools or the state setting those rules. So, I have to reflect on what has come back as part of the consultation exercise. I think these are really important aspects of our curriculum. I think if we are to achieve the four purposes, and that's how we have always got to think about it, and if we agree that those are the kind of people and individuals we want leaving our compulsory education system—how do we achieve those purposes? How are they healthy, confident individuals? How are we to prepare our children to be ethical, informed citizens of Wales and the world? So, we will reflect on what has come back to us, but I do believe that these are important aspects of the curriculum, if we are to achieve the four purposes.&#10;Speaker: Sian G" />
