    <node id="?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Okay. So, I think the first thing to realise is that our curriculum is not a copycat of the Scottish curriculum, but it is always useful to reflect on how other systems have undertaken curriculum reform in their nation and to learn from any issues that have arisen. So, I think it's fair to say—and I spent time with some delegates from Scotland just this weekend at the Atlantic Rim Collaboratory conference that Wales hosted this year. Unfortunately, Minister Swinney was not able to attend at the very last minute because of Brexit preparedness work that he was involved in, but certainly their teaching union and their equivalent of the EWC in Scotland joined us as well as representatives from the Scottish Government, although not John himself, and they were very frank about some of the challenges that they had faced in introducing their curriculum. Part of that is about assessment and they had not really thought—. They spent all their time thinking about content and spent no time at all thinking about assessment. Assessment has been a crucial part of the process that we have been involved in. Professional learning, ensuring that the profession was properly prepared for the changes, I think they would agree that that wasn't necessarily—. The middle tier, which" />
    <node id="1. Strong Leadership: This involves ensuring no segregation within schools, having high expectations for all children, and delivering a curriculum that meets the needs of each child. Strong leadership sets the tone for the school's culture and provides necessary resources and support to teachers.&#10;2. Excellent Teaching: The quality of teaching is crucial for any education system. Even if the curriculum is exciting and well-designed, its impact will be limited without effective teaching. High-quality instruction ensures that students can engage with and learn from the curriculum.&#10;3. Peer-to-Peer Sharing and Collaboration: This element emphasizes the importance of teachers working together to share knowledge, resources, and best practices. Collaborative learning environments foster innovation and continuous improvement in teaching methods.&#10;4. Differentiated Professional Learning Support: Providing tailored support for schools at various stages of curriculum implementation helps ensure that educators have the necessary skills and knowledge to effectively teach the new curriculum. This targeted assistance can be especially beneficial for teachers who may need additional guidance or training in adapting to the new pedagogical concepts introduced in the Welsh curriculum." />
    <node id=" teachers to be able to be more flexible in what they teach their children actually gives us an opportunity to deliver lessons that could be much more engaging and much more relevant to some of our schoolchildren than what they have at the moment. What will make the curriculum a success for all of our children, and I believe will have a bigger impact on children who are in danger of being left behind, are the four enabling purposes of the curriculum. So, the curriculum on its own can play a part, but it will only be as good as the four enabling elements that surround it. And that is strong leadership of our schools that ensures that there is no segregation, that has high expectation of all of our children, and delivers a curriculum within that setting that meets the needs of the children there. Secondly: excellent teaching. In the end, no education system, whatever its curriculum, can exceed the quality of the people who stand in front of our children day in, day out. So, the curriculum can be the most exciting, wonderful—and I think it is exciting and I think it's wonderful—it can be the most exciting, wonderful thing in the world, but if teachers can't teach it effectively, if their pedagogy is not excellent, then the content itself—it" />
    <node id="The requirement for delivering &quot;what matters&quot; statements is being included in primary legislation to ensure that there's a clear expectation and legal requirement for schools to deliver them. By having this requirement in primary legislation, it establishes a strong foundation for the importance of these statements. On the other hand, placing the specific wording of these statements in secondary legislation allows for easier amendments when needed.&#10;&#10;This approach acknowledges that societal understanding and priorities may change over time. By keeping the wording in secondary legislation, the Welsh government can make adjustments to the &quot;what matters&quot; statements as they work with practitioners and experts without having to go through the more rigorous process of amending primary legislation. This ensures a balance between certainty and flexibility in implementing the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;Additionally, including mental health as one of the topics in the &quot;what matters&quot; statements means that every school would have to teach mental health by law, providing greater emphasis on its importance within the health and well-being area of learning." />
    <node id="1. In October, there will be a series of three-day workshops for the Quality Improvement (QI) groups (subject specialists) to continue refining the curriculum based on feedback.&#10;2. By November, the QI groups are expected to complete their work and hand over the refined curriculum to an editorial process in both English and Welsh languages. The editorial process will then prepare the final version of the curriculum.&#10;3. Following this, the publication team will work on the website version of the curriculum, and it is set to be published in January 2020. It is important to note that the refinement process will include opportunities to improve expressions, provide greater depth, and simplify where necessary, without making significant changes to the overall concept.&#10;4. The Welsh government is also considering creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum, as recommended by the Learned Society of Wales. This proposal will be part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum." />
