    <node id="1. The Welsh government has decided to include the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in secondary legislation rather than primary legislation because it allows for easier amendments when needed, considering that societal understanding and priorities may change over time. This approach strikes a balance between certainty and flexibility in implementing the new curriculum.&#10;2. Including mental health as one of the topics in the &quot;what matters&quot; statements ensures that every school would have to teach mental health by law, providing greater emphasis on its importance within the health and well-being area of learning.&#10;3. While Suzy Davies AM suggests placing the wording of the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in primary legislation for certainty and ease of change, Kirsty Williams AM and Lynne Neagle AM explain their preference for including them in secondary legislation to ensure flexibility. The discussion also touches on addressing concerns about consistency and accountability in implementing the new curriculum." />
    <node id="1. Increased transparency and accountability: Schools in Wales will publish annual self-evaluations, which will include a broad range of measures such as progress of children, mental health, and well-being. This increased transparency will allow stakeholders to evaluate schools' performance and hold them accountable for their development plans and priorities.&#10;2. Broader evidence base for school development: The self-evaluations will not be limited to a narrow set of measures but will include various aspects of children's progress and school performance. This broader evidence base will enable schools to make more informed decisions when setting priorities and developing annual improvement plans.&#10;3. Emphasis on mental health and well-being: By including mental health and well-being in the self-evaluations, schools will be required to address these important areas in their development plans. This legal requirement will ensure that schools pay greater attention to mental health, providing students with better support and resources.&#10;4. Publication of development plans and priorities: Schools' self-evaluations will result in the publication of annual development plans and sets of priorities on their websites. This transparency will enable stakeholders to monitor schools' progress, hold them accountable for their commitments, and provide feedback when necessary.&#10;5. External evaluation by Estyn: The Welsh government has established that Estyn, the education inspectorate for Wales, will assess schools' ability to deliver self-evaluations effectively. This external evaluation will ensure a consistent standard of self-evaluation across schools in Wales and promote continuous improvement." />
    <node id="1. Viewpoint on Coordination of Responses:&#10;The speakers did not explicitly discuss the coordination of responses towards teaching RSE in the curriculum. Claire Bennett mentioned that people with a particular interest in this issue felt galvanized to respond to the White Paper on RSE, but she did not refer to it as a coordinated campaign.&#10;&#10;2. Key Messages concerning Involvement of Schools and Parents in RSE:&#10;- Kirsty Williams AM, as the Minister for Education in Wales, supports the teaching of RSE in schools and believes it is an important aspect of the curriculum. However, she acknowledges that there are concerns from some individuals who oppose the inclusion of RSE in schools. These individuals argue against its compulsory nature, believing that issues around relationships and sexuality education should not be part of the school system or curriculum but rather the preserve of parents to teach children about such matters.&#10;- Those opposing the teaching of RSE in schools also raised concerns regarding potential challenges for staff in talking about issues they may personally disagree with in relation to this curriculum. Additionally, there was a strong view that parents, and parents alone, should make decisions about whether their children should have access to the entirety of the curriculum rather than schools or the state setting those rules.&#10;- Kirsty Williams AM has indicated her intention to address the concerns raised by those who oppose the inclusion of RSE in schools, but no specific date has been provided for when she will make a statement about the government's intentions for handling these issues." />
    <node id="1. Adapting to the new curriculum: Ongoing professional learning opportunities can help teachers from different systems adapt to the new Welsh curriculum by equipping them with the necessary knowledge and skills to understand and implement its unique pedagogical concepts. This is particularly important for teachers trained outside of Wales, as it enables them to navigate and effectively teach the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;2. Attracting and retaining talented educators: By promoting ongoing professional learning, the Welsh government aims to attract and retain talented educators, positioning Wales as an attractive location for teaching professionals from other regions who are interested in working in an autonomous and dynamic educational environment. &#10;&#10;3. Supporting career development: Offering continuous professional learning opportunities demonstrates a commitment to supporting teachers' careers throughout their time in the profession. This can help attract people into teaching and encourage them to stay, as it shows that they will be consistently supported in their practice via professional learning.&#10;&#10;4. Fostering collaboration and innovation: Ongoing professional learning encourages peer-to-peer sharing and collaboration among teachers, fostering innovation and continuous improvement in teaching methods. This can create a more dynamic and engaging work environment for educators from various curriculum backgrounds.&#10;&#10;5. Addressing pedagogical differences: Acknowledging that there may be pedagogical concepts unfamiliar to teachers from different systems, ongoing professional learning can help bridge these gaps and ensure that all educators are equipped to provide high-quality instruction in the Welsh classroom." />
    <node id="1. Opposition to the inclusion of RSE in schools: Some individuals argued against the inclusion of RSE in schools, stating that it should not be a compulsory part of the curriculum and should not be taught at all within the school system. They believe that issues around relationships and sexuality education should be left solely to parents to teach children about.&#10;2. Concerns regarding potential challenges for staff: There were also concerns raised about potential difficulties for teachers when discussing RSE-related topics that they might personally disagree with, suggesting possible challenges in implementing the curriculum.&#10;3. Parental decision-making in curriculum access: A strong viewpoint was expressed that parents should have the sole authority to decide whether their children should be exposed to the entirety of the curriculum rather than schools or the state making those decisions.&#10;4. Statement on government's intentions: Kirsty Williams AM, as the Minister for Education in Wales, acknowledged these concerns and indicated her intention to make a statement about how the government will respond to these issues in the near future. No specific date has been provided yet." />
