    <edge source="Content: Yes, absolutely. I think some of the trouble that we've got ourselves in previously is because there has not been a clear distinction between assessment and accountability, and, when you start using assessment for accountability purposes, that's when, potentially, that assessment process gets corrupted and you have gaming.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Can I ask, with the assessments, though, which is about pupil progression, will those results be published internally? Will parents get to see those?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Oh, yes. And that should be the purpose for assessment. The primary purpose for assessment is for that professional to be able to know how to move that child's educational journey on, and you would absolutely expect professionals to have those conversations with parents, whether they're using formative methods of assessment or summative methods of assessment. So, absolutely, you would expect teachers to be sharing information around assessment methods, whichever type they use, with parents, to describe and to inform parents about what happens next for their child.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Right. I accept that. Is it realistic, then, to expect parents, families, communities, not to think about that information when they're" target="In the Scottish education experience, assessment played a critical role and was considered at the outset alongside the curriculum content. This approach was adopted as a result of learning from the Scottish curriculum reform process. Experts who were involved in the Scottish curriculum and assessment group have contributed to the development of coherence in their own curriculum and assessment groups by feeding in their learning throughout the process, although not in a prescriptive manner of 'don't do this because Scotland has done it'. This learning includes recognizing the importance of not using assessment for accountability purposes, which can lead to corruption and gaming.&#10;&#10;The Scottish experience also highlighted the need to think about assessment from the beginning of the curriculum development process, rather than as an afterthought. While there is no explicit mention of monitoring pupil response to the curriculum in Scotland as a way to evaluate the effectiveness of specific school curriculums, Wales has expressed interest in incorporating methods such as pupil surveys, which were used in some Canadian systems, to include pupil voice and find out what's happening.&#10;&#10;In summary, assessment played a significant role in the Scottish education experience, and experts involved in that process have contributed to the development of coherence in Wales' own curriculum and assessment groups by emphasizing the importance of considering assessment at the outset and learning from issues faced during the Scottish curriculum reform process.">
