    <edge source=" this system, and my intention is, that teachers should share assessment methods and outcomes with parents to have that conversation about what happens next. But I am absolutely clear that we do have to make this distinction between assessment for learning and an accountability in the system, otherwise we drive—inadvertently; people don't set out to do it, but we drive a set of behaviours that has negative unintended outcomes. We only have to look at the debacle around BTEC science to know that.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. I understand that. So, how—? Can you just briefly give us an indication of how you think the accountability, on both sides of that thick black line—the methodology—is likely to change with this? You mentioned that there's going to be an independent review of performance measurements coming shortly; we know that some of the existing ones have been ditched in fairly recent legislation. Without pre-empting the findings of such a review, have you got your top three likely expected changes?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: To accountability?&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: To accountability. Well, we're moving to" target="1. Kirsty Williams AM, the Minister for Education in Wales, emphasizes her support for WISERD (Wales Institute of Social and Economic Research, Data and Methods) and values their research in informing Welsh Government policies.&#10;2. Regarding Dr Nigel Newton's paper, she acknowledges that there is no concrete evidence suggesting the curriculum could exacerbate segregation within schools. However, she recognizes the importance of considering such concerns as potential unintended consequences while planning policy reforms.&#10;3. She also emphasizes that the curriculum itself will not significantly impact equity in Welsh education but rather provide opportunities for teachers to offer more engaging and relevant lessons.&#10;4. I