    <edge source=" Yes. There were 60 applicants from 170 previous pioneer schools. We've had 16—four per region. It was important that we engaged with the regions to get their view, and we've had evaluation being carried out—&#10;Speaker: Claire Bennett&#10;Content: Yes. So, during the first term of work, we asked them to really look at the curriculum as a whole—so, take the whole curriculum guidance and then think, 'How would I apply that in the school?, Does it make sense?, Can we work with it?, What are the issues?, What are the questions that arise for us for assessment?', and each of the schools produced a report setting out their reflections on, 'If I were putting this into practice—'. So, it's slightly different to the feedback we've had from other people, which has been more, 'Maybe you should emphasise this or change that wording' and kind of quite practical, and really about how you would realise this curriculum in a school. That's been drawn together into an overall report, drawing out the themes, by Wavehill, who are a kind of research company. It's been really useful, and the innovation schools met as part of the workshops last week. Having 16 headteachers in a room" target="In the Scottish education experience, assessment played a critical role and was considered at the outset alongside the curriculum content. This approach was adopted as a result of learning from the Scottish curriculum reform process. Experts who were involved in the Scottish curriculum and assessment group have contributed to the development of coherence in their own curriculum and assessment groups by feeding in their learning throughout the process, although not in a prescriptive manner of 'don't do this because Scotland has done it'. This learning includes recognizing the importance of not using assessment for accountability purposes, which can lead to corruption and gaming.&#10;&#10;The Scottish experience also highlighted the need to think about assessment from the beginning of the curriculum development process, rather than as an afterthought. While there is no explicit mention of monitoring pupil response to the curriculum in Scotland as a way to evaluate the effectiveness of specific school curriculums, Wales has expressed interest in incorporating methods such as pupil surveys, which were used in some Canadian systems, to include pupil voice and find out what's happening.&#10;&#10;In summary, assessment played a significant role in the Scottish education experience, and experts involved in that process have contributed to the development of coherence in Wales' own curriculum and assessment groups by emphasizing the importance of considering assessment at the outset and learning from issues faced during the Scottish curriculum reform process.">
