    <edge source=" Suzy. You've got a whole section on assessment, I don't know—&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: This isn't about assessment.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Oh, okay. Go on, then.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: So, on the basis that this is not about assessment, you mentioned that one of the lessons learned from Scotland is that they said they spent too much time on curriculum content rather than assessment. Can you tell me a little bit about what you've learned about how they quality control the content, even though the content, of course, will be completely different in Wales?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, the content would be completely different. When I said they spent too much time, I said that the focus had been in their work about just talking about content and, actually, the assessment arrangements were bolted on at the end of the process. So, the curriculum was all designed and developed, it was sent out to schools, and then the question was raised: 'Oh, actually, what assessment methods—? How are going to assess how children are getting on?' But, Steve, you would have more details of their" target="In the Scottish education experience, assessment played a critical role and was considered at the outset alongside the curriculum content. This approach was adopted as a result of learning from the Scottish curriculum reform process. Experts who were involved in the Scottish curriculum and assessment group have contributed to the development of coherence in their own curriculum and assessment groups by feeding in their learning throughout the process, although not in a prescriptive manner of 'don't do this because Scotland has done it'. This learning includes recognizing the importance of not using assessment for accountability purposes, which can lead to corruption and gaming.&#10;&#10;The Scottish experience also highlighted the need to think about assessment from the beginning of the curriculum development process, rather than as an afterthought. While there is no explicit mention of monitoring pupil response to the curriculum in Scotland as a way to evaluate the effectiveness of specific school curriculums, Wales has expressed interest in incorporating methods such as pupil surveys, which were used in some Canadian systems, to include pupil voice and find out what's happening.&#10;&#10;In summary, assessment played a significant role in the Scottish education experience, and experts involved in that process have contributed to the development of coherence in Wales' own curriculum and assessment groups by emphasizing the importance of considering assessment at the outset and learning from issues faced during the Scottish curriculum reform process.">
