    <edge source="1. Simplification and Clarification: Professionals have asked for some areas of the framework to be simplified and clarified, particularly regarding the language used. They are seeking clarity on whether certain concepts or topics are repeated across different Areas of Learning and Experience (AoLEs) and suggesting that these could be consolidated and streamlined to avoid repetition.&#10;2. More Detail and Depth: In contrast, professionals have also expressed a desire for more detail and depth in other areas of the framework. While they support the overall concept and principles, they believe that certain parts require further elaboration to ensure a comprehensive understanding.&#10;3. Human Rights and Children's Rights: Professionals appreciate the emphasis on human rights and children's rights throughout the design process. They acknowledge the importance of mapping these rights across each AoLE in collaboration with the children's commissioner's office.&#10;4. Assessment Proposals: The draft assessment proposals received broad support, with positive feedback for the emphasis on ongoing assessment to support children's learning and progression. However, there were suggestions to improve the expression of the purposes of assessment, as the current terminology may not be clearly understood.&#10;&#10;Overall, while professionals are generally supportive of the framework's principles and changes, they have provided feedback requesting both simplification and clarification in certain areas, as well as more detail and depth in others. The ongoing reflection process will consider this feedback to refine and improve the final curriculum before its publication in January 2020." target=" greater autonomy and agency for the profession—so, the ability of the profession to take a framework and then truly let them adapt it to meet the needs of the children that they are working with in their communities. Also, a great welcome of the emphasis on formative asses