    <edge source="1. Clear communication: The speakers emphasize the importance of clear communication to parents about the purposes and types of assessments. They propose to use distinct terms for formative (assessment for learning) and summative assessments, and explain their meanings to avoid confusion.&#10;2. Separate documents for evaluation and assessment proposals: The speakers suggest that presenting assessment results and school evaluations in separate documents can help maintain a clear distinction between the two concepts.&#10;3. Internal use of assessment results: Assessment results for pupil progression are meant for internal use by teachers, not for external accountability purposes. Keeping these results private helps prevent misuse or comparison among students, families, and communities.&#10;4. Publication of school development plans: Schools will publish self-evaluations and development plans annually to demonstrate their approach to educational improvements and child well-being. This process focuses on the school's performance as a whole rather than individual assessments.&#10;5. Teacher-parent conversations: Encouraging regular conversations between teachers and parents about a child's progress, strengths, and areas for improvement can help shift the focus from accountability to learning and development." target=" right, so schools will be publishing self-evaluations annually, or something like that?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, schools—&#10;Speaker: Steve Davies&#10;Content: The outcome of the self-evaluation is a school development plan. We expect those to be considerably enhanced.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And available.&#10;Speaker: Steve Davies&#10;Content: We expect a series of priorities for a school to set itself as a result of prioritisation. We expect that to be published through the school website, so the outcomes of that. What we're looking at, in terms of what's brought to that, is not a narrow set of measures—just two measures, or one measure in a secondary school. The measures will still consider reflection on progress of children, but it'll also have reviews of mental health, well-being, how it approaches that and things that it wanted to do. It's broadening the evidence base. The school is evaluating—the outcome of that will be a development plan, annually published on the website. Within the plan, they will have a set area of priorities that they will be publishing.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And the schools">
