    <edge source=" right, so schools will be publishing self-evaluations annually, or something like that?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, schools—&#10;Speaker: Steve Davies&#10;Content: The outcome of the self-evaluation is a school development plan. We expect those to be considerably enhanced.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And available.&#10;Speaker: Steve Davies&#10;Content: We expect a series of priorities for a school to set itself as a result of prioritisation. We expect that to be published through the school website, so the outcomes of that. What we're looking at, in terms of what's brought to that, is not a narrow set of measures—just two measures, or one measure in a secondary school. The measures will still consider reflection on progress of children, but it'll also have reviews of mental health, well-being, how it approaches that and things that it wanted to do. It's broadening the evidence base. The school is evaluating—the outcome of that will be a development plan, annually published on the website. Within the plan, they will have a set area of priorities that they will be publishing.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: And the schools" target="1. Increased transparency and accountability: Schools in Wales will publish annual self-evaluations, which will include a broad range of measures such as progress of children, mental health, and well-being. This increased transparency will allow stakeholders to evaluate schools' performance and hold them accountable for their development plans and priorities.&#10;2. Broader evidence base for school development: The self-evaluations will not be limited to a narrow set of measures but will include various aspects of children's progress and school performance. This broader evidence base will enable schools to make more informed decisions when setting priorities and developing annual improvement plans.&#10;3. Emphasis on mental health and well-being: By including mental health and well-being in the self-evaluations, schools will be required to address these important areas in their development plans. This legal requirement will ensure that schools pay greater attention to mental health, providing students with better support and resources.&#10;4. Publication of development plans and priorities: Schools' self-evaluations will result in the publication of annual development plans and sets of priorities on their websites. This transparency will enable stakeholders to monitor schools' progress, hold them accountable for their commitments, and provide feedback when necessary.&#10;5. External evaluation by Estyn: The Welsh government has established that Estyn, the education inspectorate for Wales, will assess schools' ability to deliver self-evaluations effectively. This external evaluation will ensure a consistent standard of self-evaluation across schools in Wales and promote continuous improvement.">
