    <edge source=" to us, but I do believe that these are important aspects of the curriculum, if we are to achieve the four purposes.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. You've also mentioned that there will be a final draft of the curriculum at the start of next year. What is the timetable for the Bill itself and for seeking Royal Assent for that?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Okay, so, as I said earlier, the expectation is that we will publish a final version of the curriculum in January 2020, so schools will then have the opportunity to be really engaging in it. I have to say, I'm in schools most weeks, and many, many, many schools are already taking the opportunity, even on the draft, to begin to think about planning and, indeed, changing what they're doing in schools. I'm overwhelmed, actually, by the enthusiasm of the sector to embrace what is a massive change for them. So, that's January. We would expect to introduce the Bill following the Easter recess.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Okay. That gives enough time, then, for it to be—&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams" target="1. The new curriculum is being implemented using a strategy where smaller groups of pioneer schools work together to create and test materials through cluster groups. This iterative process involves feedback from external experts, further development in pioneer schools, and refining by regions.&#10;2. Sixty applicants were chosen from 170 previous pioneer schools as innovation schools, with four per region. These schools are examining the curriculum as a whole and its practical application in their specific context.&#10;3. Wavehill, a research company, compiled reports from these innovation schools into an overall report, highlighting themes emerging from headteachers' perspectives on implementing the curriculum in their schools.&#10;4. Cluster groups play an essential role in implementing the curriculum at this stage, focusing on how individual schools can apply it in a practical manner. Regional consortia provide differentiated professional learning support for schools at various stages of implementation, emphasizing peer-to-peer sharing and collaboration.&#10;5. With a high degree of certainty about the curriculum's structure, innovation schools have been chosen for their ability to implement it in various types of schools, including secondary, primary, linguistically diverse, and faith schools.&#10;6. The final draft of the curriculum is expected to be published in January 2020, giving schools the opportunity to engage with it. Many schools are already taking advantage of this opportunity, demonstrating enthusiasm for embracing the significant changes the new curriculum brings.">
