    <edge source="The main messages received during the feedback period on the draft curriculum for the new Welsh curriculum indicate that the principles were broadly supported, with positive feedback regarding the emphasis placed on ongoing assessment to support children's learning and progression. However, there were suggestions to find a better way of expressing the purposes of assessment. The level of feedback was significant, as stated by Kirsty Williams AM, who mentioned a concerted effort and a plan drawn up to ensure that there was extensive engagement in providing feedback on the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;The Learned Society of Wales recommended creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum. This proposal is being considered as part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum, according to Kirsty Williams AM. No specific details about the extent or nature of the feedback have been provided in the transcript, but it is clear that various groups and individuals contributed to the feedback process." target=" commissioner’s quarterly report of July 2019 that consultation materials for young people were not released until mid June, allowing just over a month for young people to engage? And they said it was disappointing that a plan was not in place at the start of the consultation period.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, we undertook a specific programme of engagement with children and young people, as I said at the beginning. We had over 20 events where focus groups of young children were involved and we had a number of children who took the opportunity to feed back via different mechanisms. The output of that engagement and feedback has been drawn together into a report exploring learners' views about schools and learning. It's a powerful contribution and I think will actually effect change, especially in how the 'what matters' statements are worded.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. Siân.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Turning to the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum, the Learned Society of Wales has said that there needs to be a directory of resources to implement that Welsh dimension. Do you agree with that and">
