    <edge source="The main messages received during the feedback period on the draft curriculum for the new Welsh curriculum indicate that the principles were broadly supported, with positive feedback regarding the emphasis placed on ongoing assessment to support children's learning and progression. However, there were suggestions to find a better way of expressing the purposes of assessment. The level of feedback was significant, as stated by Kirsty Williams AM, who mentioned a concerted effort and a plan drawn up to ensure that there was extensive engagement in providing feedback on the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;The Learned Society of Wales recommended creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum. This proposal is being considered as part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum, according to Kirsty Williams AM. No specific details about the extent or nature of the feedback have been provided in the transcript, but it is clear that various groups and individuals contributed to the feedback process." target="1. In October, there will be a series of three-day workshops for the Quality Improvement (QI) groups (subject specialists) to continue refining the curriculum based on feedback.&#10;2. By November, the QI groups are expected to complete their work and hand over the refined curriculum to an editorial process in both English and Welsh languages. The editorial process will then prepare the final version of the curriculum.&#10;3. Following this, the publication team will work on the website version of the curriculum, and it is set to be published in January 2020. It is important to note that the refinement process will include opportunities to improve expressions, provide greater depth, and simplify where necessary, without making significant changes to the overall concept.&#10;4. The Welsh government is also considering creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum, as recommended by the Learned Society of Wales. This proposal will be part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum.">
