    <edge source="The main messages received during the feedback period on the draft curriculum for the new Welsh curriculum indicate that the principles were broadly supported, with positive feedback regarding the emphasis placed on ongoing assessment to support children's learning and progression. However, there were suggestions to find a better way of expressing the purposes of assessment. The level of feedback was significant, as stated by Kirsty Williams AM, who mentioned a concerted effort and a plan drawn up to ensure that there was extensive engagement in providing feedback on the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;The Learned Society of Wales recommended creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum. This proposal is being considered as part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum, according to Kirsty Williams AM. No specific details about the extent or nature of the feedback have been provided in the transcript, but it is clear that various groups and individuals contributed to the feedback process." target="1. Adapting to the new curriculum: Ongoing professional learning opportunities can help teachers from different systems adapt to the new Welsh curriculum by equipping them with the necessary knowledge and skills to understand and implement its unique pedagogical concepts. This is particularly important for teachers trained outside of Wales, as it enables them to navigate and effectively teach the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;2. Attracting and retaining talented educators: By promoting ongoing professional learning, the Welsh government aims to attract and retain talented educators, positioning Wales as an attractive location for teaching professionals from other regions who are interested in working in an autonomous and dynamic educational environment. &#10;&#10;3. Supporting career development: Offering continuous professional learning opportunities demonstrates a commitment to supporting teachers' careers throughout their time in the profession. This can help attract people into teaching and encourage them to stay, as it shows that they will be consistently supported in their practice via professional learning.&#10;&#10;4. Fostering collaboration and innovation: Ongoing professional learning encourages peer-to-peer sharing and collaboration among teachers, fostering innovation and continuous improvement in teaching methods. This can create a more dynamic and engaging work environment for educators from various curriculum backgrounds.&#10;&#10;5. Addressing pedagogical differences: Acknowledging that there may be pedagogical concepts unfamiliar to teachers from different systems, ongoing professional learning can help bridge these gaps and ensure that all educators are equipped to provide high-quality instruction in the Welsh classroom.">
