    <edge source="In the Scottish education experience, assessment played a critical role and was considered at the outset alongside the curriculum content. This approach was adopted as a result of learning from the Scottish curriculum reform process. Experts who were involved in the Scottish curriculum and assessment group have contributed to the development of coherence in their own curriculum and assessment groups by feeding in their learning throughout the process, although not in a prescriptive manner of 'don't do this because Scotland has done it'. This learning includes recognizing the importance of not using assessment for accountability purposes, which can lead to corruption and gaming.&#10;&#10;The Scottish experience also highlighted the need to think about assessment from the beginning of the curriculum development process, rather than as an afterthought. While there is no explicit mention of monitoring pupil response to the curriculum in Scotland as a way to evaluate the effectiveness of specific school curriculums, Wales has expressed interest in incorporating methods such as pupil surveys, which were used in some Canadian systems, to include pupil voice and find out what's happening.&#10;&#10;In summary, assessment played a significant role in the Scottish education experience, and experts involved in that process have contributed to the development of coherence in Wales' own curriculum and assessment groups by emphasizing the importance of considering assessment at the outset and learning from issues faced during the Scottish curriculum reform process." target=". Professional learning, ensuring that the profession was properly prepared for the changes, I think they would agree that that wasn't necessarily—. The middle tier, which they don't have to the—. Well, they've got local authorities and regions, but whether they were truly engaged in what they were doing. So, I think we've learned—. Although our curriculum isn't a copycat, as I said, we have been able to learn from, and we've had people who have been deeply involved in the Scottish experience as part of some of our curriculum and assessment groups and some of the advice that we've had in terms of developing coherence. But, Steve, I don't know if—. You speak to your Scottish colleagues quite a lot.&#10;Speaker: Steve Davies&#10;Content: As I said, they're very forthright in sharing their learning and I think one of the critical elements was the extent to which assessment was considered at the outset alongside the curriculum content. So, that was critical, but we've embraced experts who were involved in that process who were part of our curriculum assessment group. So, they feed in throughout—not 'don't do this because Scotland has done it', but they feed some of that learning into the system. As">
