    <edge source="The requirement for delivering &quot;what matters&quot; statements is being included in primary legislation to ensure that there's a clear expectation and legal requirement for schools to deliver them. By having this requirement in primary legislation, it establishes a strong foundation for the importance of these statements. On the other hand, placing the specific wording of these statements in secondary legislation allows for easier amendments when needed.&#10;&#10;This approach acknowledges that societal understanding and priorities may change over time. By keeping the wording in secondary legislation, the Welsh government can make adjustments to the &quot;what matters&quot; statements as they work with practitioners and experts without having to go through the more rigorous process of amending primary legislation. This ensures a balance between certainty and flexibility in implementing the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;Additionally, including mental health as one of the topics in the &quot;what matters&quot; statements means that every school would have to teach mental health by law, providing greater emphasis on its importance within the health and well-being area of learning." target="1. The Welsh government has decided to include the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in secondary legislation rather than primary legislation because it allows for easier amendments when needed, considering that societal understanding and priorities may change over time. This approach strikes a balance between certainty and flexibility in implementing the new curriculum.&#10;2. Including mental health as one of the topics in the &quot;what matters&quot; statements ensures that every school would have to teach mental health by law, providing greater emphasis on its importance within the health and well-being area of learning.&#10;3. While Suzy Davies AM suggests placing the wording of the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in primary legislation for certainty and ease of change, Kirsty Williams AM and Lynne Neagle AM explain their preference for including them in secondary legislation to ensure flexibility. The discussion also touches on addressing concerns about consistency and accountability in implementing the new curriculum.">
