    <edge source="The requirement for delivering &quot;what matters&quot; statements is being included in primary legislation to ensure that there's a clear expectation and legal requirement for schools to deliver them. By having this requirement in primary legislation, it establishes a strong foundation for the importance of these statements. On the other hand, placing the specific wording of these statements in secondary legislation allows for easier amendments when needed.&#10;&#10;This approach acknowledges that societal understanding and priorities may change over time. By keeping the wording in secondary legislation, the Welsh government can make adjustments to the &quot;what matters&quot; statements as they work with practitioners and experts without having to go through the more rigorous process of amending primary legislation. This ensures a balance between certainty and flexibility in implementing the new curriculum.&#10;&#10;Additionally, including mental health as one of the topics in the &quot;what matters&quot; statements means that every school would have to teach mental health by law, providing greater emphasis on its importance within the health and well-being area of learning." target="1. Increased transparency and accountability: Schools in Wales will publish annual self-evaluations, which will include a broad range of measures such as progress of children, mental health, and well-being. This increased transparency will allow stakeholders to evaluate schools' performance and hold them accountable for their development plans and priorities.&#10;2. Broader evidence base for school development: The self-evaluations will not be limited to a narrow set of measures but will include various aspects of children's progress and school performance. This broader evidence base will enable schools to make more informed decisions when setting priorities and developing annual improvement plans.&#10;3. Emphasis on mental health and well-being: By including mental health and well-being in the self-evaluations, schools will be required to address these important areas in their development plans. This legal requirement will ensure that schools pay greater attention to mental health, providing students with better support and resources.&#10;4. Publication of development plans and priorities: Schools' self-evaluations will result in the publication of annual development plans and sets of priorities on their websites. This transparency will enable stakeholders to monitor schools' progress, hold them accountable for their commitments, and provide feedback when necessary.&#10;5. External evaluation by Estyn: The Welsh government has established that Estyn, the education inspectorate for Wales, will assess schools' ability to deliver self-evaluations effectively. This external evaluation will ensure a consistent standard of self-evaluation across schools in Wales and promote continuous improvement.">
