    <edge source="1. In October, there will be a series of three-day workshops for the Quality Improvement (QI) groups (subject specialists) to continue refining the curriculum based on feedback.&#10;2. By November, the QI groups are expected to complete their work and hand over the refined curriculum to an editorial process in both English and Welsh languages. The editorial process will then prepare the final version of the curriculum.&#10;3. Following this, the publication team will work on the website version of the curriculum, and it is set to be published in January 2020. It is important to note that the refinement process will include opportunities to improve expressions, provide greater depth, and simplify where necessary, without making significant changes to the overall concept.&#10;4. The Welsh government is also considering creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum, as recommended by the Learned Society of Wales. This proposal will be part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum." target="1. The Welsh government is planning to include the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in secondary legislation within the Curriculum and Assessment (Wales) Bill. These statements outline the key components that learners need to understand and will be refined based on feedback. One such statement is mental health, which will ensure that every school teaches this topic by law, giving greater emphasis to its importance within the health and well-being area of learning.&#10;2. To ensure breadth, clarity, and national consistency in the curriculum and progression expectations for each Area of Learning and Experience (AoLE), the Welsh government is organizing three-day workshops in October for subject specialists (Quality Improvement groups) to refine the curriculum based on feedback. By November, these groups will complete their work, which will then undergo an editorial process in both English and Welsh languages. The final version of the curriculum will be prepared by this process and published on the website in January 2020. This refinement process includes improving expressions, providing greater depth, and simplifying where necessary while maintaining the overall concept.&#10;3. Additionally, the Welsh government is considering creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum, as recommended by the Learned Society of Wales. This proposal will be part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum and ensure national consistency.">
