    <edge source="1. The Welsh government has decided to include the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in secondary legislation rather than primary legislation because it allows for easier amendments when needed, considering that societal understanding and priorities may change over time. This approach strikes a balance between certainty and flexibility in implementing the new curriculum.&#10;2. Including mental health as one of the topics in the &quot;what matters&quot; statements ensures that every school would have to teach mental health by law, providing greater emphasis on its importance within the health and well-being area of learning.&#10;3. While Suzy Davies AM suggests placing the wording of the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in primary legislation for certainty and ease of change, Kirsty Williams AM and Lynne Neagle AM explain their preference for including them in secondary legislation to ensure flexibility. The discussion also touches on addressing concerns about consistency and accountability in implementing the new curriculum." target="1. The Welsh government is planning to include the &quot;what matters&quot; statements in secondary legislation within the Curriculum and Assessment (Wales) Bill. These statements outline the key components that learners need to understand and will be refined based on feedback. One such statement is mental health, which will ensure that every school teaches this topic by law, giving greater emphasis to its importance within the health and well-being area of learning.&#10;2. To ensure breadth, clarity, and national consistency in the curriculum and progression expectations for each Area of Learning and Experience (AoLE), the Welsh government is organizing three-day workshops in October for subject specialists (Quality Improvement groups) to refine the curriculum based on feedback. By November, these groups will complete their work, which will then undergo an editorial process in both English and Welsh languages. The final version of the curriculum will be prepared by this process and published on the website in January 2020. This refinement process includes improving expressions, providing greater depth, and simplifying where necessary while maintaining the overall concept.&#10;3. Additionally, the Welsh government is considering creating a directory of resources to implement the Welsh dimension in the new curriculum, as recommended by the Learned Society of Wales. This proposal will be part of the ongoing work to identify necessary resources to support the curriculum and ensure national consistency.">
